🌿 ब्रह्मगीता – ऐन्दवोपाख्यानम् (सर्ग १७८)
भाग ४ : अन्तिम शंका – निराकार और साकार का सम्बन्ध
Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178)
Part Four: The Final Objection – How Can the Formless Relate to Form?
मूल श्लोक
श्रीराम उवाच।
वाय्वन्त्रादिधरीरस्थं सर्वं सप्रतिघं मुने।
कथमप्रतिघा संविचालयेदिति मे वद॥१५॥
संविदप्रतिघाकारा यदि सप्रतिघात्मकम्।
चालयेदचलिष्यत्तद्दूरमम्भो यदिच्छया॥१६॥
सप्रतिघाप्रतिघयोर्मिथो यदि पदार्थयोः।
वेल्लनं स्यात्तदिच्छैव कर्तुकर्मेन्द्रियैः क्व किम्॥१७॥
सप्रतिघाप्रतिघयोः श्लेषो नास्ति बहिर्यथा।
तथैवान्तरहं मन्ये शेषं कथय मे मुने॥१८॥
अन्तः स्वयं योगिना वा यथैतदनुभूयते।
अमूर्तस्यैव मूर्तेन वेल्लनं तद्वदाशु मे॥१९॥

🌿 हिन्दी भावार्थ
श्रीरामचन्द्रजी अब अपनी अन्तिम शंका प्रस्तुत करते हैं।
वे कहते हैं—
हे मुनिवर!
शरीर, प्राण, इन्द्रियाँ और समस्त स्थूल जगत साकार हैं, प्रतिघातयुक्त हैं।
यदि चेतना निराकार और अप्रतिघ है,
तो वह इन स्थूल पदार्थों को कैसे संचालित करती है?
फिर वे एक अत्यन्त सूक्ष्म तर्क रखते हैं।
यदि केवल इच्छा से चेतना पदार्थ को चला सकती है,
तो दूर स्थित जल प्यासे मनुष्य की इच्छा से स्वयं उसके पास क्यों नहीं आ जाता?
यदि निराकार और साकार का प्रत्यक्ष सम्बन्ध सम्भव है,
तो इच्छा ही सब कार्य कर देनी चाहिए।
फिर हाथ, पैर, वाणी और इन्द्रियों की आवश्यकता ही क्या है?
श्रीराम आगे कहते हैं—
जैसे बाहर निराकार और साकार का प्रत्यक्ष सम्पर्क नहीं दिखाई देता,
वैसे ही भीतर भी मैं ऐसा कोई सम्पर्क स्वीकार नहीं करता।
यदि आपके पास इससे भी गहन अनुभव हो,
जो योगियों के प्रत्यक्ष अनुभव पर आधारित हो,
तो कृपा करके वही मुझे बताइये।
मैं अन्तिम सत्य जानना चाहता हूँ।

🌿 English Reflection
Sri Rama now presents his strongest philosophical challenge.
"If Consciousness is truly formless,
how can it influence a physical body?"
He pushes the argument to its logical conclusion.
If awareness alone can move matter,
why does water not come to a thirsty traveler simply because he desires it?
Why do we require hands to grasp,
feet to walk,
speech to communicate,
and senses to perceive?
If the formless directly manipulates the formed,
then mere intention should accomplish everything.
Sri Rama concludes by saying:
"I am not satisfied with partial explanations.
If yogis have directly realized a deeper truth,
please reveal it to me."
These are not the words of skepticism.
They are the voice of an earnest seeker who refuses to stop until every doubt is dissolved.

🌿 Vedantic Insight
This marks the culmination of Sri Rama's inquiry.
He has examined every conceivable explanation—
the body,
the senses,
the prāṇa,
the mind,
and even subtle consciousness as an individual principle.
Each explanation leaves unanswered questions.
Vedānta teaches that when every limited explanation fails,
the mind becomes ready to receive the limitless Truth.
True knowledge begins where speculation ends.

🌿 Practical Contemplation
Notice how often we say:
"I did this."
"I made that happen."
Vedānta quietly asks:
Who is this "I"?
The body changes.
The breath changes.
The mind changes.
Thoughts arise and disappear.
Yet something silently knows every one of these changes.
That Knower has never been seen moving.
Yet without It,
nothing could ever be known.

🌸 Living Vedanta Library Conclusion
Sri Rama has now brought human reasoning to its highest point.
No superficial answer satisfies him.
No borrowed belief comforts him.
He seeks only direct Truth.
This is the spirit of every genuine seeker.
The intellect has now reached its limit.
The next step cannot be taken by argument alone.
It requires revelation born of direct insight.
Therefore Maharshi Vasiṣṭha is about to unveil one of the most extraordinary teachings in the entire Yoga Vāsiṣṭha—
the Aindava Upākhyāna, the account of the ten Indus,
through which the apparent mystery of consciousness and creation will dissolve into the vision of non-dual Brahman.
The questions have reached their summit.
Now begins the dawn of the answer.
